<org.eclipse.epf.uma:ArtifactDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmlns:rmc="http://www.ibm.com/rmc" rmc:version="7.5.1" xmi:id="-1vAdTxGwjOISFwJR_q0rSw" name="uam_technical_location,_0nhMYNjiEdyPdoI9d5Dn-Q" guid="-1vAdTxGwjOISFwJR_q0rSw" authors="DW Enstrom" changeDate="2015-02-12T15:09:19.081-0500" changeDescription="New" version="2.0.1">
  <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    A Technical Location defines the locations where the enterprise has a presence that it implements and manages.&#xD;
    Technical level activities, devices, and processes are defined that are found at the locations. Locations are a&#xD;
    categorization of locations, based upon the technical (business) functions supported, with having processes and&#xD;
    services that are under the authority of the enterprise (or system) in question. This element provides the ability to&#xD;
    manage complexity in architectures through the definition of hierarchical models.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h5>&#xD;
    Note&#xD;
&lt;/h5>&#xD;
&lt;p class=&quot;BodyTable&quot; style=&quot;MARGIN: 6pt 0in&quot;>&#xD;
    This is only one type of location modeling element. The complete list is summarize here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a&#xD;
    class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../UAM/guidances/supportingmaterials/uam_tpl_simple_FA24A330.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_w5B_8EWJEeOfR_FtRm9PUg&quot;>Supporting Material: TPL Summary&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
  <purpose>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Locations&amp;nbsp;are a categorization, based upon&amp;nbsp;the technical (business) functions supported, of&amp;nbsp;locations&#xD;
    with&amp;nbsp;technical systems under the authority of the enterprise (or portion) in question.&amp;nbsp;In addition to&#xD;
    Enterprise or Domain Architects, the following people use these locations:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;b>System designers&lt;/b>, when describing business points of presence&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;b>User-interface designers&lt;/b>, as input to capturing characteristics on&amp;nbsp;roles&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Network designers&lt;/strong>, as input into understanding the network design requirements&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;b>System analysts&lt;/b>, as input to finding&amp;nbsp;interfaces and protocols&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul></purpose>
  <representationOptions>&lt;p>&#xD;
    A Technical Location&amp;nbsp;are the physical level locations at which the system&amp;nbsp;under study has a presence. Each&#xD;
    location is defined in terms of the Technical Activities present and provided at the location along with the types of&#xD;
    communications required and provided between these locations. Defined here is the top-level location, which contains&#xD;
    (hierarchically) other types of location modeling elements.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>UML Representation&lt;/strong>:&amp;nbsp;«stereotype» TPL_Location&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>Extends:&lt;/strong> «metaclass» Node&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    It has the following &lt;strong>properties&lt;/strong>:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>id: string&amp;nbsp;-&lt;/strong> This attribute is used to uniquely identify elements.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>name: string&amp;nbsp;-&lt;/strong> A descriptive name for the location.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>activities: Activities[0..*]&lt;/strong>&amp;nbsp;- A list of the business activities provides at the location,&#xD;
        which relates directly to the Technical Process Model and how the business (or system under study) wants to deliver&#xD;
        its products and services.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>nonFunctional: string&lt;/strong>&amp;nbsp;- Defines things such as business importance, survivability, and&#xD;
        availability requirements of the location.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>description: string&lt;/strong>&amp;nbsp;- A description of the location in terms of building, address or other&#xD;
        distinguishing characteristics.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;h5>&#xD;
    Constraints&#xD;
&lt;/h5>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Shall not have any owned operations;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Shall not have any owned behaviors;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        May have relationships with only Technical Domains or with Technical Activities (provided at the location);&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        May contain Technical Zones;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        May communicate with other Locations via Technical Communications;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        All owned properties shall be public.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;h5>&#xD;
    Note&#xD;
&lt;/h5>&#xD;
&lt;p class=&quot;BodyTable&quot; style=&quot;MARGIN: 6pt 0in&quot;>&#xD;
    This is only one type of location modeling element. The complete list is summarize here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a&#xD;
    class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../UAM/guidances/supportingmaterials/uam_tpl_simple_FA24A330.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_w5B_8EWJEeOfR_FtRm9PUg&quot;>Supporting Material: TPL Summary&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p></representationOptions>
